# Navigating Filesystems in Powershell

## Lab Overview
This lab will cover how to manipulate filesystems using cmdlets

- Understand how Powershell is different from CLI, even though it shares some simularities.
- Identify the main cmdlets used by IT professionals for working with filesystems
- Learn how this aspect of Powershell relates to cybersecurity

## Key Concepts

| Get-ChildItem | lists items inside a location. Can work with folders, file systems, registries or certificate stores |
| -Path | Paramenter. signals a specific path or location |
| Set-Location | cmdlet used to move to a different location on the system |
| New-Item | creates a new item(such as a file, directory or registry) and allows user to set its value |
| Remove-Item | deletes items(such as folders, registry keys, variables, aliases and functions)

## Environment

Platform: TryHackMe  
Operating System: Windows Server 2019
Instance: Windows Powershell

## Lab Walkthrough

### Syntax: Get-ChildItem
PS C:\Users\example> Get-ChildItem 

    Directory: C:\Users\example

Mode                 LastWriteTime         Length Name
----                 -------------         ------ ----
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Desktop
d-r---          9/4/2024  10:58 AM                Documents
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Downloads
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Favorites
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Links
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Music
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Pictures
d-----          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Saved Games
d-r---          5/8/2021   9:15 AM                Videos
- Mode(Shows item type and attributes)
- d(directory/folder)
- r(read-only attribute, cannont be edited, overwritten or deleted)
- LastWriteTime(last time the folder was modified)
- Length(the size of file, folders do not show bytes)

### Syntax: Set-Location

PS C:\Users\example> Set-Location -Path ".\Documents"
PS C:\Users\example\Documents> 
- changed location from C:\Users\example to C:\Users\example\Documents
- Set-Location(changes where the session is pointed)
- Path(signals a specific location)
- .\Documents(how the Documents folder is designated in Powershell)

### Syntax: New-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe" -ItemType "Directory"

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents> New-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe" -ItemType "Directory"

    Directory: C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin

Mode                 LastWriteTime         Length Name
----                 -------------         ------ ----
d-----          9/4/2024  12:20 PM                captain-wardrobe

### Syntax: New-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe\captain-boots.txt" -ItemType "File"  

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents> New-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe\captain-boots.txt" -ItemType "File"     

    Directory: C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe

Mode                 LastWriteTime         Length Name
----                 -------------         ------ ----
-a----          9/4/2024  11:46 AM              0 captain-boots.txt
- created a new folder named "captain-wardrobe" inside C:\Users\example\Documents\captain-cabin
- Itemtype "Directory"(the new item is a folder)
- created a new item called "captain-boots.txt" within a folder named captain-cabin

### Syntax: Remove-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe\captain-boots.txt"

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents> Remove-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe\captain-boots.txt"
PS C:\Users\captain\Documents> Remove-Item -Path ".\captain-cabin\captain-wardrobe" 
- removed file named captain-boots.txt
- removed folder named captain-wardrobe.txt
- when the item was removed, there was no output
- removing an item that holds items init may require "-Recurse"

### Syntax: Get-Content -Path ".\captain-hat.txt"

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin> Get-Content -Path ".\captain-hat.txt"

## Security Relevance
- filesystems can be seen as a layer of investigation or possible abuse
- these basic commands are used by by both attacker and defenders for inspection, creation, modifiation and removal
- Get-Childitem can be used as a discovery tool for the presents of suspicious items
- Set-Location is common tool for navigation. Allows quick traversal through folders and logs
